Implemented Vercel Web Analytics for the Next.js clinic application

## Changes Made:

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics package
- Added `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1 as a project dependency
- Updated package.json and package-lock.json accordingly

### 2. Configured Analytics in Root Layout
Modified: `src/app/layout.tsx`
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next';`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag after the children component
- Follows Next.js App Router pattern as specified in official Vercel documentation

## Implementation Details:

This is a Next.js 16.2.1 application using the App Router pattern. Following the official Vercel Analytics quickstart guide, I:

1. Fetched the latest installation instructions from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart
2. Identified the project uses Next.js App Router (src/app directory structure)
3. Installed the package using npm (the project's package manager)
4. Added the Analytics component to the root layout file (src/app/layout.tsx)

The Analytics component is placed at the end of the body tag, which is the recommended position per Vercel's documentation. This ensures analytics tracking will be active across all pages of the application.

## Verification:

✓ Build completed successfully with no errors
✓ TypeScript compilation passed
✓ All dependencies installed correctly
✓ No lint errors (no linter configured in project)
✓ No test failures (no tests configured in project)

## Next Steps for Deployment:

To enable analytics tracking in production:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Navigate to the Analytics section in the Vercel dashboard
3. Click "Enable" to activate Web Analytics for this project

The analytics will automatically start tracking page views and web vitals once enabled in the dashboard.
